case_vignette: A 34-year-old woman arrives to your office complaining of a recurrent rash. The first time the patient noticed the rash was after going in the water at the beach six weeks ago. She reports that since then, she has developed similar appearing pink and itchy rashes on her arms and legs. She states that the rashes eventually resolve on their own. The patient works as a forest ranger at a national park. Her medical history is significant for systemic lupus erythematous and asthma. Her current medications include NSAIDS and an albuterol inhaler. She reports that she has seasonal allergies but no food intolerances. Her temperature is 98°F (36.7°C), pulse is 70/min, blood pressure is 118/77 mmHg, respirations are 13/min, and oxygen saturation is 98% on room air.
